#: ..\..\source\DCCIntegrations\Softimage\intro.rst:4
msgid "**Fabric for Softimage**"
msgstr ""

#: ..\..\source\DCCIntegrations\Softimage\intro.rst:6
msgid ""
"Fabric for Softimage is the integration of Fabric Canvas in Autodesk "
"Softimage."
msgstr ""

#: ..\..\source\DCCIntegrations\Softimage\intro.rst:8
msgid ""
"The plugin allows you to use Fabric inside your Softimage projects for tasks"
" such as creating complex procedural geometry, loading assets (e.g. Alembic,"
" FBX), drawing directly into the viewports and controlling the "
"transformation of objects (e.g. for rigging)."
msgstr ""

#: ..\..\source\DCCIntegrations\Softimage\intro.rst:10
msgid ""
"The heart of Fabric for Softimage is a custom operator, called *CanvasOp*, "
"which ensures communication between Softimage and Fabric and which can "
"access kinematic states and polygon meshes."
msgstr ""

#: ..\..\source\DCCIntegrations\Softimage\intro.rst:12
msgid ""
"Furthermore, an extensive set of custom commands is provided to create "
"Fabric operators and entire graphs via scripting."
msgstr ""

#: ..\..\source\DCCIntegrations\Softimage\intro.rst:14
msgid "**Splice for Softimage** (legacy)"
msgstr ""

#: ..\..\source\DCCIntegrations\Softimage\intro.rst:16
msgid ""
"Splice for Softimage is the legacy integration of Fabric Engine inside "
"Autodesk Softimage."
msgstr ""

#: ..\..\source\DCCIntegrations\Softimage\intro.rst:18
msgid ""
"The plugin provides custom user interfaces and a custom operator called "
":dfn:`SpliceOp` that can access kinematic states as well as polygon meshes."
msgstr ""

#: ..\..\source\DCCIntegrations\Softimage\intro.rst:20
msgid ""
"This custom operator can drive elements in the scene and is perfectly suited"
" for implementing rigging as well as procedural geometry tools."
msgstr ""

#: ..\..\source\DCCIntegrations\Softimage\intro.rst:22
msgid ""
"Splice for Softimage is not integrated into ICE (but can access ICE data), "
"and geometry types other than polygon meshes such as Curves, Nurbs or "
"Particles are not supported."
msgstr ""
